        <h2 id="examples">Real GBP verification examples</h2>

        <h3>1. Standard dental practice</h3>
        <p>Dr. Kim opens a new practice, creates a GBP listing, and selects postcard verification. The postcard arrives within 7 days. She enters the 5-digit PIN in the GBP dashboard, and full verification completes within 24 hours. She can now respond to the 3 reviews left during the waiting period and publish her first GBP post announcing the practice opening.</p>

        <h3>2. Mobile dog grooming service — video verification</h3>
        <p>Jake's mobile grooming service operates from a branded van with no fixed storefront. Google requires video verification for service-area businesses in his category. Jake records a 2-minute video showing his van's exterior branding, grooming equipment, business license, and the city streets he operates in. Approved within 48 hours with no postcard delivery required.</p>

        <h3>3. Multi-location gym chain — bulk verification</h3>
        <p>A regional gym chain with 14 locations uses GBP's bulk verification process. They submit a single verification form covering all 14 listings. Approval took 9 days. All 14 listings became active simultaneously, saving the equivalent of 14 individual postcard timelines — a 9-day process instead of potentially 14 weeks.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">GBP Verification vs Google Guaranteed — what is the difference?</h2>
        <p>These are two distinct programmes that are frequently confused by business owners.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>GBP Verification</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Free — no cost to verify</li>
              <li>Confirms business ownership and address</li>
              <li>Unlocks standard GBP management features</li>
              <li>Required for Map Pack eligibility</li>
              <li>Takes days to weeks</li>
              <li>Available to all business types</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Google Guaranteed</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Paid — tied to Local Services Ads spend</li>
              <li>Requires background checks and insurance proof</li>
              <li>Displays green trust badge on your listing</li>
              <li>Unlocks Local Services Ads placement</li>
              <li>Takes weeks to months to complete</li>
              <li>Limited to select service categories</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">6 best practices for smooth GBP verification</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Start verification before you need it.</strong> The postcard process takes up to 14 business days. Begin the moment you create your listing — do not wait until a campaign or opening is imminent.</li>
          <li><strong>Use your exact legal business name.</strong> Adding keywords to the name during creation risks immediate suspension after verification. Use the name on your business license.</li>
          <li><strong>Ensure mailbox accessibility.</strong> For postcard verification, ensure someone will collect mail at the listed address during the 14-day window. Missed postcards require requesting a new one and starting the clock again.</li>
          <li><strong>Prepare video documentation in advance.</strong> If you are in a category likely to require video verification (locksmiths, plumbers, legal services, mobile services), have your business license, branded materials, and location ready before you begin.</li>
          <li><strong>Connect to Google Search Console first.</strong> If your website is verified in Search Console, many business profiles qualify for instant verification — skipping the postcard process entirely.</li>
          <li><strong>Stay active post-verification.</strong> Listings that go dormant after verification signal low engagement. Google's local algorithm rewards active, regularly-updated profiles with consistent posts, photo uploads, and review responses.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — editing address mid-verification</div>
          <p>Changing your business address after requesting a verification postcard cancels the request and restarts the process. Make sure your address is final before selecting a verification method. Multiple address changes in a short window can also trigger a manual review that adds further delays.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common GBP verification mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Requesting postcard verification to an address you do not control.</strong> If the postcard is delivered to a shared coworking space and goes uncollected, the PIN expires and you restart.</li>
          <li><strong>Creating a new listing when an unverified one already exists.</strong> Search for your business before creating — if an unclaimed listing exists, claiming it preserves any existing reviews and ranking history.</li>
          <li><strong>Using a personal Gmail instead of a business account.</strong> Managing GBP through a business Google Workspace account gives you better access controls and makes agency handoffs cleaner.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring the verification email in spam.</strong> Email verification codes have short expiry windows. Check spam folders if you do not see the email within 30 minutes of requesting it.</li>
          <li><strong>Not re-verifying after an address change.</strong> Moving premises without triggering re-verification leaves your listing pointing to an outdated address — a guideline violation that risks suspension.</li>
        </ul>

